      "web_research": {
        "results": [
          {
            "possibleIdentity": "Adrianne Wortzel (born 1941) is a New York-based pioneering media artist and painter whose career spans over six decades. During the late 1960s and 1970s, Wortzel's early work was characterized by abstract painting and early experiments with kinetic elements. In the mid-1960s, she created motorized geometric three-dimensional sculptures, such as pyramid-like carpets that were designed to appear as if they were \"breathing,\" serving as early precursors to her later time-based and robotic work. Her paintings from this era often explored the intersection of organic movement and formal structure. She was mentored by prominent artists including Ad Reinhardt, Louise Bourgeois, Jimmy Ernst, and Isaac Soyer at Brooklyn College and the Brooklyn Museum Art School. While her later work from the 1990s onward became widely known for integrating robotics, telerobotics, and electronic literature, her early practice aligned with the spirit of the Experiments in Art and Technology (E.A.T.) movement by seeking to bridge the gap between art and engineering. Her work has been supported by the National Science Foundation and the Robert Rauschenberg Foundation, and is held in collections such as the Moderna Museet in Stockholm and the Whitney Museum of American Art.",
